                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">6. Understanding Inspection Levels &amp; AQL</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">AQL (Acceptable Quality Limit) is the foundation of statistical quality control. It defines the maximum percentage of defective items allowed in a batch. Understanding AQL helps balance quality needs with production realities.</p>
                    
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-slate-200 mb-6">
                        <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-4">Standard AQL Levels for Chargers</h3>
                        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                            <table class="w-full text-sm">
                                <thead class="bg-slate-100">
                                    <tr>
                                        <th class="text-left p-3 font-black text-brandBlue uppercase">Defect Type</th>
                                        <th class="text-left p-3 font-black text-brandBlue uppercase">AQL Level</th>
                                        <th class="text-left p-3 font-black text-brandBlue uppercase">Example Defects</th>
                                    </tr>
                                </thead>
                                <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-100">
                                    <tr>
                                        <td class="p-3 font-semibold text-red-600">Critical</td>
                                        <td class="p-3">0.0 or 0.065</td>
                                        <td class="p-3">Safety hazard, electric shock risk, fire hazard</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td class="p-3 font-semibold text-amber-600">Major</td>
                                        <td class="p-3">1.0 or 1.5</td>
                                        <td class="p-3">Performance failure, wrong voltage output, broken enclosure</td>
                                    </tr>
                                    <tr>
                                        <td class="p-3 font-semibold text-green-600">Minor</td>
                                        <td class="p-3">2.5 or 4.0</td>
                                        <td class="p-3">Minor scratches, color variation, loose packaging</td>
                                    </tr>
                                </tbody>
                            </table>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-slate-200 mb-6">
                        <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-4">Sample Size Based on Batch Quantity</h3>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3">Using ISO 2859-1 inspection level II:</p>
                        <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-1">
                            <li>Batch of 1,201-3,200 units &rarr;Sample 125 units</li>
                            <li>Batch of 3,201-10,000 units &rarr;Sample 200 units</li>
                            <li>Batch of 10,001-35,000 units &rarr;Sample 315 units</li>
                            <li>Batch of 35,001-150,000 units &rarr;Sample 500 units</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm"><strong>WOWOHCOOL Standard:</strong> We use stricter internal AQL levels (Critical: 0.0, Major: 0.65, Minor: 1.5) than most clients require, catching issues before they reach your market.</p>
